   <text>
      <body>
         <div type="letter">
            <pb n="1" facs="Edgeworth_Princeton_C1664_unknown_02_page01.jpg"/>
            <opener>
               <salute> Dear <persName> <abbr type="title">Mr.</abbr> Rogers</persName>
                  <persName>
                  </persName>
               </salute>
            </opener>
            <p>
               This is not the first time that you have<lb/>
               been called upon by me to act as arbiter<lb/>
               elegantiarum &amp; to decide our family<lb/>
               disputes on the rights and wrongs of the<lb/>
               English language.<lb/></p>
               <p>
               And farther &amp; especially to settle the<lb/>
               usages as to certain phrases, to <choice><orig>deter<lb/>
               -mine</orig><reg>determine</reg></choice> whether they be such as are <choice><orig>deem<lb/>
               -ed</orig><reg>deemed</reg></choice> exclusively Irish consequently vulgar,<lb/>
               or whether though they may not be<lb/>
               sanctioned by <persName>Johnson</persName> or <persName>Lowth</persName><lb/>
               nor by any grammar nor any <choice><orig>diction<lb/>
               -ary </orig><reg>dictionary</reg></choice>they may be thought naturalized<lb/>
               in England by long use among well-<lb/>
               bred people - &amp; no more to be subject<lb/>
               to the brand of vulgarity nor to be<lb/>
               pursued by the hue &amp; cry of Bad English.<lb/>
               Bad English - Irish Irish Irish!<lb/></p>
               <p>The question was asked<lb/>
               "Did the bell ring?"<lb/>
               Instead of answer being made to this<lb/>
               question an objection was raised - It<lb/>
               was observed that the question should<lb/>
               have been "Has the bell rung?"<lb/>
               Did the bell ring"  the objector thinks<lb/>
               is not English but Irish - The objector<lb/>
               does not found the objection upon the <choice><orig>evi-<lb/>
            <pb n="2" facs="Edgeworth_Princeton_C1664_unknown_02_page02.jpg"/>
               dent</orig><reg>evident</reg></choice> impossibility of the bell's signing<lb/>
                  itself withouten hands" such an  <hi rend = "underline">objection</hi><lb/>
               would in truth attach equally to the<lb/>
               phrase "Has the bell rung."<lb/>
               which in strict grammatical propriety<lb/>
               ought to be Has the bell <del>rung</del>been rung?<lb/>
               But laying aside this last question for<lb/>
               the purist - the present objector <choice><orig>con-<lb/>
                  ceives</orig><reg>conceives</reg></choice> that the word <hi rend = "underline">did</hi>should not<lb/>
               be used in this sentence or in similar<lb/>
               cases without reference to a fixed &amp;<lb/>
               specified time past - as thus<lb/>
               <hi rend = "underline">Did the bell ring</hi> yesterday?<lb/>
               at two oclock?<lb/></p>
               <p>The individual who gave occasion<lb/>
               to the discussion by the question charged<lb/>
               to - (Did the bell ring) holds to it never<lb/>
               -theless &amp; conceives that the time past<lb/>
               is implied with sufficient definiteness &amp;<lb/>
               need not in common parlance &amp; for<lb/>
               the main purposes of speech i e to be<lb/>
               understood completely be marked by<lb/>
               added words --<lb/></p>
               <p>Defendant farther conceives or<lb/>
               conceits that the question Did the<lb/>
               bell ring - might be asked in <placeName>England</placeName><lb/>
               as well as in <placeName>Ireland</placeName>, &amp; that it would not<lb/>
            <pb n="3" facs="Edgeworth_Princeton_C1664_unknown_02_page03.jpg"/>
               in good company be pronounced to be<lb/>
               either bad English or good Irish<lb/>
               Defendant having nothing farther to say<lb/>
               says no more &amp; here the argument &amp; the<lb/>
               dispute together rest, awaiting the result<lb/>
               of reference. -<lb/></p>
            <p>The parties <del>it is to be understood</del> it is<lb/>
               to be observed did not get to such high<lb/>
               words as did <persName xml:id="SibtC1"> <choice><orig>Col<hi rend = "superscript">l</hi></orig><reg> <roleName type="honorific" full="abb"> Col.</roleName></reg></choice>Sibthorpe</persName> &amp; the <persName xml:id="RussJ1"><roleName type ="honorific">Lord</roleName><lb/>
               John Russell</persName> in a late debate in the<lb/>
               <placeName>House of Commons</placeName>. The objector did<lb/>
               not absolutely declare that the phrase<lb/>
               used by his opponent was "inconsistent<lb/>
               with common sense as well as English<lb/>
               grammar"<lb/></p>
               <p>Nor did the defendant think proper <lb/>
               in reply to declare against learning<lb/>
               either grammar or common sense in<lb/>
                  anything else from the Hon<hi rend = "superscript">ble</hi> objector<lb/></p>
               <p>-- Nor does the defendant brandish<lb/>
               high the British sword (or the Irish)<lb/>
               nor offer the satisfaction of a gentleman<lb/>
               for a fault in grammar nor proceed to the<lb/>
               military mode of <hi rend = "underline">cutting</hi> the gordian knot<lb/>
               which he cannot untie. On the contrary<lb/>
             <pb n="4" facs="Edgeworth_Princeton_C1664_unknown_02_page04.jpg"/> 
               both parties prefer having a recourse<lb/>
               to civil decision &amp; agree to refer the<lb/>
               matter to a judge to whose practical<lb/>
               skill &amp; theoretic knowledge in speaking<lb/>
               as well as writing the English language<lb/>
               they with perfect respect both equally<lb/>
               bow down --<lb/></p>
            <p><persName>M<hi rend = "superscript">r</hi> Rogers</persName>' decision is impatiently<lb/>
               though humbly awaited by the parties<lb/>
               who mean while refrain from touching<lb/>
               upon the question of bell ringing &amp; abstain<lb/>
               from the use of the word <hi rend = "underline">did</hi> altogether.<lb/></p>
            <closer>
               Signed by order for her Self &amp; company<lb/>
               <persName>ME</persName><lb/>
            </closer>
            <postscript>
               <p>PS. When bickering hot<lb/>
                  To high words got<lb/>
                  Break out at Galliorum<lb/>
                  The golden rule<lb/>
                  In every school<lb/>
                  To push about the forum<lb/>
                  If it were not beneath the dignity of the<lb/>
                  author of the pleasures of Memory he is<lb/>
                  requested to say if he know what is <choice><orig>Galli-<lb/>
                  -orum</orig><reg>Galliorum</reg></choice> -- whether it be a real name in<lb/>
                  sober certainty or existing only in<lb/>
                  the brain of those who are engaged in<lb/>
                  pushing about the forum --<lb/>
                  <persName>M E</persName><lb/></p>
            </postscript>
         </div>
